{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060057A/1930102501/0580.xml":{"full_text":"A-2\n20 KILLED, 35 HURT\nON GERMAN VESSEL\nShot Fired by Brazilian Fort\nDeclared Intended Only\nas Warning.\n(Continued Prom first Pi|e.)\nballot, obligatory education, uniformity\nIn taxes. Plans also call for the even\ntual convocation of a new Congress\ncomposed of 12 representatives from\neach State.\nFavor Natives of Brasil.\nIt also Is planned that In the future\nonly native bom Brasilians shall occupy\npublic office.\nAs a prelude to obtaining recogni\ntion abroad, the foreign ministry has\nnotified diplomatic and consular rep\nresentatives in foreign countries that\nthe revolution which upset the govern\nment In Rio de Janeiro was a blood\nless affair, conducted with order, and\nthat Its aim was to unite the Brazilian\npeople in one family.\nTelegrams exchanged between heads\nof the Junta and those In charge of the\nStates which backed the revolution of\nthree weeks ago are wholly congratula\ntory In character and stir the belief\nhere that the revolutionists in the field\nwill Join with those In the capital In\nworking out some form of new govern\nment.\nTavora May Defy Rio.\nDispatches from the north Indicate,\nhowever, that Capt. Juarez Tavora may\nhave Ideas of his own as to constitution\nof a new regime. This officer, who\nbegan the revolt In the Northern State\nof Pernambuco and accumulated a large\narmy as he pushed through the States\nof Parahyba, Alagoas, Serglpe and down\nInto Bahia, Is expected here by airplane.\nThe deposed President, Washington\nLula, was still held a prisoner today In\nFort Copacabana. Revolutionary au\nthorities said this morning that the\nformer Executive had not actually\nsigned a decree of resignation but had\nbowed to the will of the military men.\nIn Rio de Janeiro business went on\naa usual this morning, with stores and\ncoffee shops open. No alcoholic bever\nages were sold, however, by order of\nthe chief of police. This official also\nordered that no person could leave the\ncapital without a pass for safe conduct\nIssued by his department.\nDr. Luis held out for hours against\nresignation with the words that he\nwould be taken from Ouanabra Palace\nonly when he had been bound hand and\nfoot. Later he consented to the military\njunta\u2019s demands.\nCardinal Takes Hand.\nHis decision finally was made at the\ncounsel of Cardinal Lame and Mon\nsignor Rosalvo Costa Rego, vicar gen\neral of the Rio de Janeiro diocese. He\nleft the palsce In the company of the\ncardinal, the vicar general and Oen.\nTasso Fragoeo. As he passed through\nthe reception room he bade good-by to\nthe assembled ministers of his cabinet\nand members of the civil and military\nhousehold.\nOutside the two ecclesiastics and Oen.\nTasso Pragoso entered an automobile\nwith him. Other heavily armed offi\ncers mounted the running board as the\ndeposed President was whisked away\nfrom the scene of his nearly-completed\nfour-year term as chief executive of\nthe Brazilian Union to the fort.\nThere is little apparent animosity\ntoward the deposed President, who\ngenerally was regarded as honest In his\nconvictions, but surrounded with a mili\ntary and official family which many In\nthe nation found objectionable.\nJustice Minister Held.\nThe military Junta In Its night-long\nmeeting, decided to hold the deposed\nminister of Justice, Vienna do Castello,\nand the deposed minister of war. Oen.\nBesefredo doe Passes, as prisoners, set\nting at liberty other members of the\ncabinet, all of whom had been arrested.\nDispatches from Sao Paulo said Presi\ndent-elect Julio Preetes, who but tor\nthe revolution would have succeeded\nDr. Washington Luis November 18, had\ndisappeared. There were rumor* that\nhe had fled the city In an airplane.\nIn an orgy of destruction yesterday\ndamage estimated at 11,000.000 was\ndone to seven newspaper offices and\nbuildings by gangs of hoodlums. Troops\nand police today guarded strategic\ncenters.\nNewspapers Are Damaged.\nThe newspapers A Nolte, O Jomal do\nBrasil, O Palz, Vanguardta, A Notlcla,\nCritic* and A Ordem all suffered In\nthe rioting. Movable property was\nthrown from windows into the streets\nand everything Inflammable was burn\ned. Fawcets were opened In the build\nings and streams o( water seeped\nthrough them damaging property of\nother offices.\nS&o Paulo dispatches said that quiet\nprevailed there, but that there was con\nsiderable uncertainty as to what moves\nwere to be expected of the \"federal\u201d and\n\"rebel\u201d armies still aligned against\neach other, although not fighting, along\nthe Parana-Sao Paulo frontier. State\noffices were deserted by officials yester\nday after some firing on the government\npalace. It was expected that a pro\nvisional government would be formed\ntoday.\nBecause of the censorship which the\ngovernment invoked at the ports still\nunder its control, advices of the coup\nwere received outside this country yes\nterday with surprise, but residents of\nthe capital had known for days that\nIt was Impending, many believing that\nit would be postponed so as to allow\nthe president to conclude his term\nNovember lfi.\nSoagbi Btoodteoa Chang*.\nIt is believed, however, that the mili\ntary figures who led In the coup de\ncided to prevent further bloodshed and\nacted sooner. According to the best\nInformation, two generals, two ad\nmirals and Cardinal Leme went to\nOuanabara Palace Thursday night and\nurged him to resign, but he refused\nAt 2:30 am. the entire barracks and\nmilitary police were aroused and sent\nto guard the palace. Dr. Luis was\nasked to resign again and was given\nuntil XI S.m., but he refused stlU.\nLeaders of the coup, recognizing that\nhe had fallen, even though still refus\ning the technicality of his signature\nto abdication papers, announced his\ndeposition and resignation. As a matter\nof fact It was not until late Friday\nevening that he finally acquiesced in\ntheir demands and left the palace under\nguard to become a prisoner.\nCrowds gathered to cheer his deposi\ntion, and the Red colors of the Liberal\nParty, which has opposed the admin\nistration, were to be seen everywhere.\nr. 8. AWAITS DEVELOPMENTS.\nStatus of Military Junta Affects Qucs\ntton of Recognition.\nSr the Associated Press.\nThe questionable status of the mili\ntary Junta which has seised the gov\nernment of Brazil from the administra\n-1 tion of Washington Luis raised the\nproblem today of the relations which\nwill exist between the new regime and\nI the Washington Government.\nNews dispatches that some of the\nrevolutionary officers would not support\nthe new regime add confusion to the\nconsiderations and speculations here\nof the recongnltlon of the military\ncommittee's control by the United\ni states.\nThe normal course has been for the\nt United States to extend almost lmme\ni recognition to a Latin American\nrepublic when it is convinced the new\nrevolutionary government controls the\ncountry and has received pubUe sup\nport. The extent of the support to be\nAmin the new regime by evolutionary\nleaders Is expected here to give con\nsiderable weight to any /ctimtjlowerd\nI recognition bythe United Stag*\ni The only word received by the State\nBAKER CASE EXPERT WITNESS SKETCHED ON STAND\nk\n\nAt top: Assistant United States Attorney William H. Collins, CoL Calvin Goddard, ballistic expert, and Lucian Van\ndoren of defense counsel, conferring on photographic plates taken es bullets extracted from Miso Maty Baker\u2019s body.\nLeft: Col. Goddard as be was testifying that the bullets that killed Mias Baker were fired from the pistol turned over to\nauthorities by Herbert M. Campbell, the defendant. At right: Campbell was sketched as he listened attentively to Col.\nGoddard\u2019s testimony. \u2014Sketched by James T. Berryman, Star Staff Artist.\nBRAZILIAN ENVOIS\nCAREER DESCRIBED\nHeld Diplomatic Posts in\nNine Countries Before\nComing to U. S.\nMr ths Associated Press.\nAmbassador S. Gurgel do Amaral,\nwho represented the Washington Luis\ngovernment in the United States during\nthe turbulent weeks preceding its fall\nand remains as Brasil\u2019s accredited rep\nresentative, is the third oldest diplomat\nin Washington In point of service.\nWhen first news of the Brazilian over\nturn reached Washington yesterday, the\nAssociated Press telephoned Ambassador\ndo Amaral, who had received no word\nof it.\nInformed of the dispatch, he was un\nderstood to say:\n\"How absurd!\u201d\nLater the Ambassador said he had\nmade no such remark.\nThe Associated Press gladly presents\nthis statement and regrets that there\nshould have been any misunderstanding\nabout the matter.\nDiplomat Since ISM.\nA career man with service dating\nback to 1896, the Brazilian Ambassador\ncame to Washington in June, 193 ft.\nEarlier he had served as first secretary\nin Rio do Janeiro since Ambassador\nMorgan\u2019s message yesterday reporting\nofficially the overthrow of the govern\nment was a brief one saying that for\npurposes of protection the former Presi\ndent has been moved from the presi\ndential palace to Fort Capacabana.\nThe Post Office Department said to\nday that mall from Brazil was being\nhandled in the usual manner without\nInterruption. The service Is by ship,\nairmail not yet having been Inaugurated\nto that country.\nVARGAS SEES VICTORY.\nPONTA GROSSA. Parana, Brazil,\nOctober 25 (JP).\u2014Oetullo Vargas, who Is\naccepted in the south as head of the\nBrazilian revolutionary movement. In\nCommenting on the overthrow of the\nWashington Luis administration In Rio\nde Janeiro, today told the Associated\nPress: \"Triumph of the revolution Is\na victory of the people, and revindicates\nthe program of the Liberal party (of\nwhich Vargas Is head).\n\"Since the triumph has been attained\nby force of arms, political reforms for\nwhich the revolution was struggling will\nperhaps be more radical than if our\nvictory had been obtained at the polls.\nThus we have no compromise with the\nstate of things which we find.\n\"With regard to international policy,\nBrazil will seek to strengthen the bonds\nof friendship with all American nations\nand to fulfill an International agree\nments.\u2019\u2019\nTAVORA MAT DEFT JUNTA.\nPERNAMBUCO, Brazil, October 25\n(iP). \u2014Capt. Juarez Tavora, commanding\nthe Northern Revolutionary Army, today\nnotified the federal garrison commander\nat Vahla that he himself was not yet\nready to take orders from the military\nJunta which has taken over the govern\nment at Rio de Janeiro.\nCapt. Tavora, who has been advanc\ning with an army of volunteers and\nformer federals from the State of\nSerglpe to Bahia, sent a message to\nthe general commanding there demand\ning nis surrender. The Bahia general\nreplied that he would obey orders of\nthe Junta at Rio.\nCapt. Tavora telegraphed back that\nbe would be glad if the general would\ngve in and avoid useless bloodshed, but\nat he was indifferent as to whether\nthe general accepted his authority. He\ndeclared that he himself would not\nreceive orders from the junta until\nthe Junta swears obedience to the basic\nprinciples of democratization and\nmoralization of the regime, for which\nhe and the other civil and military\nrevolutlonlarles of all Brazil have\nfought.\nHo continued that when he had ar\nrived at the city of Bahia he Intended\nto organize in the name of the people\na provisional government under a re\nsponsible civilian, for, he said, \"military\nmen do not revolt to gain positions and\nmilitary men who adhered to the revo\nlution at the eleventh hour are not\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY, OCTOBER 25, 1930.\nunder the first Brazilian Ambassador to\nthe United States, Dr. Jooqulm Nabuco,\nfrom 1905.\nAmbassador do Amaral yields seniority\nto Ambassador Manuel C. Tellez of\nMexico, who last Winter became dean\nof the diplomatic corps, and to Ambas\nsador Nobile Giacomo de Martino of\nItaly, who came in March, 1925. Am\nbassador Tellez came to Washington in\nFebruary that year.\nAmbassador do Amaral\u2019s first ap\npointment, shortly after he had gradu\nated from the Sao Paulo faculty of law,\nwas as second secretary to the Brazilian\nlegation at the Court of Russia In 1898.\nHe later served In the same capacity\nin Spain, Uruguay, Great Britain and\nArgentina, occupying the latter poet\nfrom 1903 to 1905.\nGot U. B. Poet While la Chile.\nIn 1909 ho was transferred from\nWashington to London, and two years\nlater was raised to the rank of Minister,\nserving In that capacity In Paraguay,\nHolland, and Germany. While In Ger\nmany the question of Brazilian neu\ntrality In the World War arose and\nended in severed relations with Ger\nmany and Brazil\u2019s entry Into the war\non the side of the allies.\nAmbassador Do Amaral represented\nhis government as special Ambassador\nat the celebration commemorating the\nfirst centenary of Peruvian Inde\npendence in 1922, when the Brazilian\nlegation In Chile was raised to the rank\nof an embassy, he was appointed Am\nbassador to that country.\nIt was while he wee serving In Chile\nthat he was named Ambassador to the\nUnited States.\n6. U. SEISMOGRAPH\nRECORDS TWO QUAKES\nShock at 7:12 A.M. Today Believed\nCentered 3,400 Miles From\nWashington.\nAn earthquake, beginning at 7:12\na.m., today and estimated to have been\ncentered 3,400 miles from Washington,\nwas recorded on the seismograph of\nGeorgetown University Setemological\nObservatory. The direction from\nWashington could not bo determined.\nAnother disturbance, described as the\nmost severe noted in the past two\nmonths, was recorded yesterday at\nGeorgetown, beginning at 3:30 p.m.\nand continuing for more than three\nhours.\nThe quake reached Its greatest In\ntensity at 4:15 p.m., and observatory\nofficiate estimated its center as about'\n7,000 miles from Washington.\nOTHER SHOCKS FELT\nDENVER, October 25.\u2014An earth\nquake believed to have occurred In\nAlaska was registered on the Regis\nCollege seismograph early today.\nFather Armand W. Foretell, in charge\nof the Instrument, said the disturbance\nstarted at 5:23 am. (M. 8. T.) and\ncontinued for 17 minutes. He was un\nable to determine the degree of in\ntensity of the shocks.\nYesterday, the seismologist reported,\ntwo quakes were registered. The first\nand strongest occurred at 1:37 p.m.\n(M. S. T.) and continued for alx min\nutes. The second came at 2 p.m. and\nlasted 15 minutes. Father Forstall Was\nof the opinion the first of Friday\u2019s quakes\noccurred on the North American con\ntinent, and the second one was more\ndistant and probably more severe.\nBRAZILIAN SHIP DOCKS\nTO TAKE ON AIRPLANES\ni Special Dispatch to Tha Star.\nBALTIMORE, October 2ft.\u2014Here to\ntake abroad three large bombing planes\nfrom the local Glenn H. Martin plant,\nwhich will be used in her country\u2019s fight\nagainst the revolutionists, the Brazilian\nsteamer Atalala yesterday docked at\nthe Pennsylvania Railroad\u2019s pier at\nCanton.\nAlthough the Government at Wash\nlngton has decreed that the United\nStates may support the Brazilian gov\ni eminent in its fight against the rebels\nby supplying whatever accessories of\ni war are needed. Vinlclo de Velgo, local\nBrazilian consul, said that no arrange\nmenu had been made to ship any guns\nI or ammunition on the Atalala.\ns The Atalala, which is one of the first\nsteamers flying the Brazilian flag to\nvisit this port In a long time, was for\n-1 merly owned by the Gaw\u00dfan govern\npent, but was seised dufifir the Werld\nWar and was added to the South Amer-\nPROSECUTOR PLANS\nTO SHOW GUN TEST\nCollins Not to Withdraw Chal\nr. lenge Despite Counsel for\nHerbert Campbell.\n(Continued From First Page.)\nconsultation with Albert H. Hamil\nton, ballistic expert for the de\nfense, Smith announced his decision to\nwithdraw his acceptance and to make\na counter proposal as already outlined.\nThe defense explained that the Jury\nwas interested only In Campbell's gun\nand not in a variety of other weapons.\nCollins contended today that the\ncounter offer was \"foolish and ridicu\nlous\" because both Goddard and Hamil\nton already have made exhaustive tests\nof Campbell's gun and of the bulleU\nfired therefrom and that Goddard al\nready has explained to the jury his\ntheories and findings with respect to\nwhat the Government alleges Is the\nfatal weapon. If Hamilton cares to\nexplain his theories at a proper time,\nthat Is another matter, It was pointed\nout.\n\"I hold that the defense, and par\nticularly Mr. Hamilton, aTe afraid to go\nthrough with my proposition. That\nproposition stands. I will tell the court\nthe offer was made In good faith and\nthat I can see no reason for not carry\ning out the original plans as agreed\nupon yesterday.\u201d\nWill Borrow Mlcrooeopo.\nCol. Ooddard said he would ask for\nthe loan of a comparison microscope by\nthe Bureau of Standards. He said he\nIs willing to use the microscope which\nDr. Wilmer Souder, Government bal\nlistics expert, used In his examination\nof Campbell\u2019s gun and the fatal bullets.\nSouder, like Goddard, found that the\nmortal slugs were fired from the .32\ncaliber revolver voluntarily turned over\nto authorities by the accused Arlington\nCounty realty dealer.\nAdvised of plans of the defense to\nproduce in court a pair of pigskin\ngloves which, it Is claimed, are the ones\nwhich were missing from Campbell's\nhouse after the murder of Mary\u2019 Baker,\nCollins remarked, \"This Is pretty\nlate date to be bringing them forward.\u201d\nThe Government contends that a slml\nl&r pair of gloves, found in a sewer\ntrap on the Arlington Experimental\nFarm, beside some of the Baker girl\u2019s\nclothing, were at one time Identified by\nCampbell as his.\nAccepts Challenge.\nIt was at the conclusion of direct\nexamination of Goddard that Collins\nhurled his challenge at the defense.\nHe said:\n\"Are you satisfied to have five or six\npistols selected at random, have bullets\nfired from thorn anywhere In the pres\nence of the Jury and then have Col.\nGoddard examine the bullets and tell\nyou from which guns they were fired.\u201d\nSmith promptly replied, \"We accept.\u201d\nWhile Godaard was on the stand\nearlier In the day, Collins produced a\ndozen or so sets of numerous photo\ngraphs of the mortal and test bullets\nmade by the witness and his assistants.\nThe pictures were distributed among\nthe jurors while Goddard was asked to\nexplain their significance. He declared\nmarks on the test bullets correspond\nwith scratches on the death slugs. This,\nhe contended, proved the fatal bullets\nwere fired from Campbell's revolver.\nGoddard stepped down from the wit\nness stand on several occasions to peer\nover the shoulders of the jurors and\nanswer their questions concerning varl\nous striations on the bullets as made\nvisible by the photographs.\nInspected Pictures Hour.\nThe Jurors inspected with care for\nnearly an hour the sets of photographs\nof fatal and test bullets offered by the\nwitness. There was no Intimation from\ntbe Jury box, however, concerning\nl whether the lines matched as the wit\nneas testified. Photographs of the test\ni bullets were superimposed over pictures\nr of the actual death slugs,\ni Collins Introduced In evidence the\nnegatives from which the photographs\ni were made as a result of a pre-trial re\nquest of defense counsel.\nLuclen H. Vandoren of defense eoun\ni sel, objected to Introduction of the pic\nturn on tha grounds that there was\nno shewing of the method or manner\nI of the taking of the pictures. After\nJustice Adkins overruled, the objection\nADM. C. W. DYSON\nDIES ATAGE OF 69\nRetired Naval Officer Had\nUntil Recently Been on Duty\nWith Claims Board.\nRear Admiral Charles W. Dyson,\nU. 8. N\u201e retired, died today at the\nNaval Hospital here. Until recently he\nwas on duty with the Naval War Claims\nBoard at the Navy Department.\nNaval officials announced this after\nnoon that funeral services will be held\nat 3 o'clock Tuesday afternoon at the\nWatiilngton Cathedral. Following this\nInterment will be In Arlington National\nCemetery, with full military honors.\nPresident Hoover awarded the Dis\ntinguished Service Medal to Admiral\nDyson for designing the propellers of\nthe aircraft carriers Saratoga And\nLexington and for other naval vessels,\nas he was considered \"one of the fore\nmost authorities in the world In the\nfield of propeller designing.\u201d\nBorn at Cambridge, Md., December 2,\n1861, Admiral Dyson was appointed a\nnaval cadet engineer In 1679 and he\nGraduated from the Naval Academy\ni 1883.\nAdmiral Dyson served the Navy In\nvarious parts of the world and on many\nof its vessels. He was on duty In\nWashington In the design division of\nthe Bureau of Engineering and served\nas chief designer from 1906 to 1910,\nand In charge of the division from\n1910 to 1913, when he became Inspector\nof machinery at the New York Ship\nbuilding Co. at Camden, N. J.\nThe admiral came back to Wash\nington to the Bureau of Engineering\nIn December, 1914, where he served\ncontinuously In charge of the design\ndivision until March, 1922, when he\nbecame inspector general of engineering\nfor the Bureau of Engineering. This\nposition he held until he was retired\nfor age in 1925.\nFor his World War service In Im\nmediate charge of work on design of\nmachinery for destroyers, eagle Mots,\nsubmarine chasers, mine sweepers and\nthe conversion of various civilian ships\nto naval use, he was awarded tne\nNavy Cross.\nAdmiral Dyson\u2019s home address wss\n1840 Lamont street.\nRELIEFORGANIZED\nIN NEW YORK CITY\nPolice Stations to Be Center of Dis\ntribution\u2014Census of Idle\nBeing Taken.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 25.\u2014A commit\ntee composed of the heads of the city\u2019s\n37 departments was In charge today of\nplans for relief of the unemployed.\nPolice stations have been designated\nas distribution centers for food, clothing\nand fuel. Distribution of necessities will\nbegin as soon as the Police Department\nhas completed Its enumeration of those\nin need of help. Police Commissioner\nMulrooney said he expected the unem\nployment census would be completed by\nMonday. The first eight hours\u2019 canvass,\nhe said, listed 9,641 families whose\nbreadwinners were out of work.\nFunds for the city\u2019s relief work are\nto be provided from private contribu\ntions and by appropriation from the\ncity treasury. A special item of $1,000,-\n000 for unemployment relief has been\nincluded In the 1931 budget.\nAt the meeting yesterday, at which\nMayor Walker organized the commit-1\ntee of department heads with himself\nas chairman, It was suggested salaried\nemployes of the city donate 1 per cent\nof their monthly salaries for six months.\nIt was estimated this would bring a\nmonthly fund of aMut $226,000.\nDonations of food will be asked from\ndealers, hotels and other sources.\nImmediate action also was planned to\nconvert piers, markets and various other\navailable city buildings into dormitories\nto house the homeless.\nThe Salvation Army opened eight\nsoup kitchens In various parts of the\ncity yesterday.\nACCOUNT OF ALTERCATION\nIS CALLED INACCURATE\nPlace of Clash Between Oscar H.\nXee and James V. Cherlco\nDefined by Attorney.\nMaurice M. Grubb, counsel for Oscar\nH. Kee of the 600 block of Buchanan\nstreet, who was cleared Thursday in a\npolice case growing out of an alterca\ntion. today advised The Star that a\nmisinterpretation had been placed on\nthe circumstances in the account pub\nlished of the affair.\nKee climaxed trouble with James V.\nCherlco of the 600 block of Columbia\nroad over Cherico\u2019s reputed attentions\nto Mrs. Kee, by hitting him with an\nautomobile jack handle. The district\nattorney\u2019s office held he wss justified\nand refused to press charges.\nIn the account of the case. It was\nstated that \"police said Kee caught\nCherlco with his wife\u201d at the time of\nthe clash.\nGrubb, however, explains that Kee\nwas taking his wife home, and finding\nCherlco in front of her home, struck\nhim.\nWREPEPCO GIRLS GIVE\nPARTY ON ANNIVERSARY\n125 Employes of Washington Rail\nway A Electric and Potomac Elec\ntric Power Companies Attend.\nThe fifth anniversary of the found\ning of the Wrepepco Girls\u2019 Club is be\ning celebrated today at Peter Pan Inn,\nat Urbana, Md.. by 125 girls from the\nPotomac Electric Power Co. and the\nWashington Railway 6c Electric Co.\nMiss Mabel Loftus, president of the\nclub, and Mrs. Whitman Harper, chair\nman of entertainment, arranged the\nafternoon\u2019s program, which consists of\na luncheon, athletic events and danc\ning. A caravan of motor busses of\ntbe Washington Railway 6c Electric\nCo. transported the club members to\nthe Inn.\nThe Wrepepco Girls\u2019 Chib, organized\nIn 1925, was formed for the purpose of\npromoting a closer relationship and\nunderstanding among employes. These\ngirls, employed In the many depart\nments of Pepco and Wreco, have joined\nin numerous affairs of the club. Funds\nraised at these affairs have, on many\noccasions, been used to assist worthy\ncharitable organizations.\nHonor guests of the anniversary party\nwere past presidents of the Wrepepco\nGirls\u2019 Club. These Include Miss Eliza\nbeth J. Dolan, the club's first president,\nand Mrs. May B. Blakeney.\nNORWAY LABORITES LOSE\nReduction of 12 Seats Suffered in\nStorting Election.\nOSLO, Norway, October 23 (A*).\u2014The\nLaborites lost 12 seats in the Norwe\ngian general elections Monday, com\nplete returns revealed yesterday. They\nnow have only 47 Deputies In the\nStorting.\nAll of the 12 seats went to the Con\nservative party.\nTbe turnover wurt Interpreted In po\nlitical circles as blow at Com\nmunism, some policies of which tbe\nFOUNDLING LEFT IN ARLINGTON COUNTY\nTMML_LI \u2014\u2014\u2014\u00a5ll J l\nV ;M| f| i'-'i\nt jj i.,\n.i* _ i _ ,i\u00a3?\ns4s >y y v v<\ni\ni|P\n\nt !in\u00abWpwf pi\nx srpl p*\nV\nl -,MSfflM**^*\u2018^^^^ WmfflP^\u2122~'*-'\nThis 1-WNk-tU btbjr boy *u found loot night on the steps letdini from\nRoaalyn to Colonial HeifhU, and now la In the Georgetown University Hospital.\nWearing apparel and blankets wore In a traveling bag found beside the infant.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nBABY IS LEFT ON ROSSLYN STEPS\nWITH CLOTHES AND FOOD\nAbandoned Child Well Wrapped in Blankets, With Sur\nplus Nearby, Taken to Hospital.\nBy a Staff Correspondent ot The Star.\nARLINGTON COUNTY COURT\nHOUSE. Vft., October 25.\u201450 warmly\nwrapped that no cold could reach It*\nlittle body, a 7-weeks-old baby wa*\nfound abandoned last night on the steps\nleading from Rosslyn to Colonial Heights\nand Is now being cared for in George\ntown Hospital, apparently none the\nworse for its experience.\nThe baby, a boy, was discovered by\nMrs. Paul Twine, who lives nearby, is\nshe was going down the steps on her\nway to Washington. The Infant was\nasleep. In which state it continued so\npeacefully after it was taken to the\nhome of Maj. and Mrs. Maxwell G.\nKeeler, that an investigation led to the\nbelief that a sedative had been placed\nin Its milk.\nBeside the infant was a traveling bag\ncontaining a large amount of clothing,\nwhich Included not only wearing apparel\nbut blankets as well. Mrs. Keeler said\ntoday that while the clothing was not\nPRESIDENT SCOUTS\nNEED OF SPECIAL\nSESSION ON JOBS\n(Continued From First\nto compile figures on unemployment\n!in the metropolitan areas most\nseriously affected.\nCroxton to Arrive Monday.\nFred C. Croxton of Columbus, Ohio,\nwill arrive in Washington Monday to\ntake up his duties as director of relief\nin the Middle West.\nWhile in New York Col. Woods plans\nto recruit two or three other persons for\nteglonal work, particularly with In\ndustry.\nWoods said he understood conditions\nin New England were not as serious as\nin other densely populated areas.\n\u201cThe City of Irvington, N. J.,\u201d he said,\n\u201cshould be an object lesson to other\ncities similarly situated. A municipal\nemployment bureau has been organised\nand more than a thousand employers\nin that metropolitan area are furnish\ning them with opportunities for work.\nSchools, parents and teachers\u2019 leagues,\nchambers of commerce, fraternities, civic\norders and the Salvation Army are\nworking intensively for the unemployed.\nTheir daily broadcasting, movie appeals\nand advertising have been exceptionally\nhelpful.\u201d\nChamber es Commerce Plans Cited.\n\"As an index of what the Chamber\nof Commerce can do,\u201d he continued,\n\u201clet me cite the example of the Wil\nliamsburg Chamber of Commerce,\nBrooklyn, N. Y., which, in order to\nImprove business and help to decrease\nunemployment, adopted and carried\nout the following plans:\n\u201cIt made a complete housing survey\nof its entire section and then set up a\nDistrict Planning Committee which\nsucceeded in interesting a group of\nwealthy builders who pledged to invest\nover $5,000,000 to start the rehabilita\ntion of Williamsburg. This chamber\nhas also organized a Financial Advisory\nCommittee to help finance builders In\nalterations and new construction work.\n\"It also organised a committee of\nmerchandising experts to help the mer\nchants in group buying, improved dis\nplays, improved retail sales, and group\nadvertising. The chamber also is help\ning to place unemployed through its\nmerchant and manufacture members.\u201d\ngeonts Need es Extra Seeaien.\nExisting agencies are, in the expressed\nopinion of President Hoover, sufficient\nto meet present emergencies without\ncalling a special session of Congress.\nMr. Hoover let it be known in an\nnouncing that suggestions for an ex\ntraordinary congressional session met\nwith his disapproval.\nAt the same time the Chief Executive\nsigned an order through which, it is\nestimated, 200,000 family heads may se\ncure employment in the postal service\nduring the Christmas rush.\nIn making known his opinion that\nno special congressional session was\nneeded to deal with employment, Mr.\nHoover said:\n\u201cThe sense of voluntary organization\nand community service in the American\npeople has not vanished. The spirit of\nvoluntary service has been strong\nenough to cope with the problem for\nthe past'year and it will, I am confi\ndent. continue in full measure of the\nneed.\u201d\nRegarding the bond proposals. Woods\nurged local leaders to study them care\nfully and if they considered them\nworthy, to give them their support.\nMost of the issues, he continued, en\ntailed the employment of labor, and\nwould result in the stimulation of in\ndustry by increasing the buying power\nof the workers.\nSUIT IS DISMISSED\nDiscovery and Accounting Action\nBrought Against Mackay.\nJustice Cox in Circuit Division S has\ndismissed a suit for dlsoevery and\naccounting brought by John Broumas\nand eight other Greeks against Vasil\nMackey, trustee, and others in connec\ntion with the affairs es the Vgell Steen\nHeating Oorporatlon JPhs court allowed\n16 days to the plaintiffs to saaad their\nof the beet quality and had been made\nby some one who apparently was inex\npert with the needle, it was clean.\nIn order that the baby should be\nequipped with sufficient rations to last\nout the night, a glass Jar containing\nmilk for several feedings had been left\nbeside the traveling bag. The Infant\nhad apparently been placed there but\na short time before it was found and\nhad been fed Just before that.\nMaJ. Keeler went to tlfe Arlington\nCounty Jail for advice and returned\nwith an officer and Mrs. Mae E. Jacobs,\nsuperintendent of public welfare. Mrs.\nJacobs took charge of the Infant and\ntook U to the hospital, where it is being\ncared for until the completion of an\ninvestigation, which is under way today.\nMrs. Jacobs stated that while the it*\nwas nothing in the clothing to lead to\nthe identification of the person aban\ndoning the baby, she did have a clue\nwhich she hoped might prove fruitful\nbefore the end of the day.\nSTORM DRENCHES.\nROYAL GUESTS AT\nASSISI WEDDING\n(Continued From First Page.)\nheld out for Giovanna, who is a pretty\nblond girl of 22, but a sudden burst of\nrain caught her and wet her dress\nbadly.\nSo great was the congestion of motor\ncars about the church that others, in\ncluding some of the highest royal fig\nures of Europe, were not afforded even\nthis protection and many were drenched.\nBy the time Boris arrived at the church\nthe rain had turned to hail and he\nand his suite were badly battered.\ninside the church the bridal party\nhad difficulty in forming for the march\ndown the center aisle of the historic\nedifice to the altar, but after some de\nlay this was done, and while the choir\nof 120 voices sang the stirring Latin\ninvocation \u201cO Lord Make Base Our 1\nKing\u201d they circled about the altar for\nthe ceremony.\nFather Risso, custodian of the basilica,\nread the marriage ceremony, which was\nbrief, in keeping with a union in matri\nmony of a Roman Catholic and a non-\nRoman Catholic. The ceremony Itself\nwas possible only by special dispensa\ntion of the Pope, who ruled that Gio\nvanna might marry Boris if any chil\ndren bom of the marriage be brought\nup in the Roman Churqb and if there\nwas no succeeding Oreek Catholic cere\nmony.\nCheered by Crowd of 3,0 M.\nAfter a short speech of congratulation\nand benediction from Father Risso the\nroyal bride and groom left the upper\nchurch for the lower for a reverential\nvisit to the tomb of St. Francis, which\nis located there. Once again the wed\nding party strode through the driving\nrain, gowns and gay regalia sagging\npathetically from the dampening.\nA crowd of 3,000 or so had remained\nnot far from the church, despite the\nrain, and they cheered loudly as the\nparty appeared. Princess Giovanna,\nwho, while she was inside the church,\nhad become Queen Giovanna, smiled\ngraciously. Boris seemed preoccupied.\nDuring the wedding and visits to the\nlower church and ctypt of St. Francis\nPrincess Giovanna was frequently in\ntears. She did not recover her com\nposure until she left the church, when\nthe sight of 300 Assisi children strew\ning white roses in her path brought\nback her dimpled smile.\nGiovanna wore a white gown with a\nhigh neck and long sleeves. Its very\nshort train was borne by two officers of\nthe court. Boris wore a dark-blue full\nuniform of a Bulgarian general with red\nfacings, red sash and multi-colored\ndecorations. Former Czar Ferdinand,\nBoris\u2019 father, was dressed like the groom.\nHe limped painfully as he walked down\nthe aisle, using a gold-headed cane.\nParty Goes to City Hall.\nAfter the ceremony at the church\nthe party Went to the city hall, where\nthe marriage was entered upon the civil\nregisters in accordance with Italian law.\nJust at noon Giovanna appeared in the\ndoorway on the arm of her soldier hus\nband. Both smiled with pleasure as\nthe massed bands broke into the Bul\ngarian national anthem and as the\ncrowd of 3,000 or more below cheered\nthem. From all windows facing the\nsauare rich bits of tapestry and flags\nof the two countries were displayed.\nIn the train behind the bride and\ngroom as they proceeded from the upper\nchurch and the lower church and the\ncrypt of St. Francis were the King and\nQueen of Italy, Victor Emanuel and\nElena: former Queen Sophie of Greece,\nthe former Csar Ferdinand of Bulgaria\nand 54 princes and princesses from all\nover Europe. Premier Mussolini, in full\nministerialist costume, brought up the\nrear.\nThe bride\u2019s witnesses at the wedding\nwere Crown Prince Humbert and Count\nCalvl de Bergolo, husband of her sis\nter Yolanda. At the City Hall Prince\nPhilip of Hesse, husband of her sister\nMafakia, and the Duke of Aosta at\ntested to her marriage. In both cere\nmonies Prlnco Cyril, brother of Boris,\nand the Duke of Wuertemberg acted for\nAfter the two ceremonies the party\nwent to the Villa Costansa, where the\nwedding breakfast was held. The menu\nconsisted of especially prepared eggs,\nlobster, roast pheasant frop royal pre-\nSCHWAB PREDICTS\nBUSINESS REVIVAL\n\nLeading Industrialist Cites\nNumerous Projects Which\nGuarantee Employment.\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 35.\u2014The augury\nof a greater progperity \"than America\nhas ever before known\u2019* was sounded\nyesterday by Charles M. Schwab.\nIt was echoed by other outstanding\nIndustrialists; It was mirrored In the\nmovement of stocks; and It found symp\ntoms of support In developments them\nselves.\nThe Federal Government, through Its\ndirector of unemployment relief, Col.\nArthur Woods, pointed the way bv\nwhich local governments might \"go far\ntoward relieving unemployment\" In\nabout 20 States. Public works Involving\nthe expenditure of approximately 9430-\n000,000 and the consequent employment\nof many thousands of persons can be\nstarted, he indicated. If voters approve\nbond Issues up for decision at the No\nvember elections.\nEmployment Drive In Cities.\nIn Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee and\nBuffalo announcements were made of\nmen being called back to work.\nChicago\u2019s plans, both to provide work\nand relief, began taking concrete shape.\nA group of New York banks Inaug\nurated a campaign to boost business\nrecovery by discouraging what Is called\nthe \u201cfalse economy\u201d of persons not\ndirectly affected by general employ\nment conditions.\nIn Wall Street, the first anniversary\nof \"Black Thursday\u201d was marked by\na strong and optimistic tone, contrast\ning sharply with that of a year ago.\nActive stocks finished the day from\ntwo to five points higher.\nFinancial Set-Back Noted.\nUnfavorable financial news of the\nday Included the announcement by\nMontgomery Ward 6c Co. of the omis\nsion of the regular dividend; but even\nthis stock, sinking to a new low after\nthe dividend omission announcement,\nmade partial recovery before the market\nclosed.\nThe Schwab statement was made be\nfore the American Iron 6c Steel Insti\ntute. Mr. Schwab regarded the \"level\nheaded way in which business In gen\neral has weathered the current reces\nsion\u201d as \"most assuring.\u201d\n\nTWO SAVED AS AUTO\nPLUNGES INTO WATER\nAT FOUR-MILE RUN\n(\u2022Continued From First Page.)\noff and with the aid of Officer Beyliss,\nwho had waded Into the stream,\nbrought her ashore.\nStrobel then swam to the culvert\nwhere the water is about 12 feet deep\nand brought Coldwell out and with the\naid of Officers Bayllss and Elmore and\na rope which another motorist produced,\nbrought him to shore, Thinking that\nthere might be still another person m\nthe water, Strobel dived several times\nand only stopped when Caldwell told\nthe officers to tell him there were only\ntwo persons in the car.\nStrobel and Miss Simpson were taken\nto the Alexandria Hospital for treat\nment for exposure and a few slight\ncuts. Strobel was released from that\ninstitution as soon as dry clothing was\nobtained and Miss Simpson expects to\nleave the hospital today.\nScene of Ten Accidents. 9\nThe \"Death Trap\u201d barrier has been\nthe scene of 10 accidents since it was\nerected on the completion of the wide\nArlington County portion of the high\nway a few months ago. This Is the first\ntime, however, that a car has plunged\nentirely through it and gone into the\nstream below. Numerous protests have\nbeen made by local and Arlington\nCounty officials to the State Highway\nCommission and a conference between\nJ. C. Albright, district engineer of the\ncommission, and local and county heads\nhas already been scheduled to con\nsider proper lighting for the barrier.\nMiss Simpson, who Is the daughter\nof Arthur L. and Emma R. Simpson,\nis employed at the Columbia Whole\nsalers, Inc., at 1619 L street northwest.\nStrobel, who is a widower with several\nsmall children, Is an ironworker for\nthe General Fireproof Co., Ninth and\nGirard streets northeast, Washington,\nD. C.\nCONFERENCE ARRANGED.\nSteps to Eliminate \"Death Trap\u201d Will\nBe Taken November S.\nBy a Staff Correspondent of The Star.\nARLINGTON COUNTY COURT\nHOUSE, Va., October 25.\u2014Just prior\nto an accident in which an automobile\nplunged through the guard rail Into\nthe water at Four-milt Run, Common\nwealth\u2019s Attorney William C. Gloth,\nlast night completed plans for a con\nference on November 3 In an effort to\neliminate the \"death trap\u201d at the point\nwhere the Washington-Alexandila pike\ncrosses Four-mile Run.\nArrangements for the conference\nwere made between Gloth and J. C.\nAlbright, a strict engineer for the Vir\nginia State Highway Commission.\nIn addition to Gloth and Albright,\nthose to take part In the conference\nare the Board of Supervisors of Ar\nlington Count, County Directing Engi\nneer C. L. Kinnier, and City Manager\nWallace Lawrence and City Engineer E.\nC. Dunn of Alexandria.\nSteps toward the elimination of this\nsituation, which was brought about by\nthe widening, by the State Highway\nCommission, of the northern end of the\nroad, that portion which remains In\nAlexandria and the bridge being left\nthe original width, were first taken at\nthe last meeting of the Board of Super\nvisors when Chairman Edward Duncan\nasked that the State officials be asked\nto meet the local authorities for a dis\ncussion. Upon Albright\u2019s acceptance.\nDuncan Instructed Gloth to Invite the\nparticipation of the Alexandria officials.\nMcADOO TO FLY WEST\nWill Take Son and Secretary to\nLos Angeles in Monoplane.\nNEWARK, N. J., October 25 VP)\u2014\nWilliam G. McAdoo, former Secretary\nof the Treasury, plans to take off at\n10 a.m. today for Los Angeles In his\nmonoplane \u201cBlue Streak.\" His son,\nRobert, and his secretary, Miss Vera\nWard, will go with him.\nLast week McAdoo flew from Los\nAngeles to Newark In 16 hours and SO*\nminutes to determine \"how fast the\naverage business man could make the\ntrip.\u201d\n\nKingsford-Smith Given Boomerang.\nSYDNEY, October 25 OP).\u2014Kings\nford-Bmith, the flyer, has a boomerang,\nsymbolic, as the mayor said at a pres\nentation, of a man who always gets\nthere and always gets back.\nBAND CONCERT.\nBy the United States Soldiers' Home\nMilitary Band, this evening, at Stanley\nHall, at 5:30 o\u2019clock; John Zimmerman,\nbandmaster: assistant.\nSSfScte\u2014sEsu.tlon'\u2019 Drumm\nf *\u00aes Arabian Serenade\u201d\nExcerpts from the musical comedy\n\u201cOh Kay\u201d Gershwin\nBut-trot. \u201cI Still Get a Thrill\u201d.. ,ooo*f\nrape. S \"Arouad b the","height":"25527","width":"19794"}}
